You can try with `CallableStatement`, that comes with `java.sql` package.

First of all you have to create and open the connection. For this I usually use an Sql2o instance for connecting to a specific database.

So:

    Sql2o sql2o = new Sql2o(dbUrl, dbUser, dbPass);
    Connection conn = sql2o.open();
    CallableStatement cstmt = conn.getJdbcConnection().prepareCall(&quot;{call your_stored_procedure(?,?,?,?,?,?,?,?,?)}&quot;)

The questions marks are the number of IN/OUT arguments of your stored.
To set the arguments:

    cstmt.setObject(1,your_value, Types.INTEGER);
    cstmt.setObject(2, your_value, Types.DOUBLE);
    ... // set all your arguments
    cstmt.execute();

if you have also out parameter in your stored you can register it with

    cstmt.registerOutParameter(8, java.sql.Types.INTEGER);

The first argument of `cstmt.setObject()` is the parameter index of your stored procedure

Since a recent version of ojdbc, and Oracle 18c, you can finally bind PL/SQL `TABLE OF RECORD` types just like a SQL `TABLE OF OBJECT` type, using standard JDBC API. For this, you have to implement a Java representation of your `RECORD`, which implements [`java.sql.SQLData`][1]:

```java
class MyType implements SQLData {
    // Constructors, getters, and setters

    @Override
    public String getSQLTypeName() throws SQLException {
        return &quot;P.MY_TYPE&quot;;
    }

    @Override
    public final void readSQL(SQLInput stream, String typeName)
    throws SQLException {
        this.val1 = stream.readInt();
        // ...
    }

    @Override
    public final void writeSQL(SQLOutput stream)
    throws SQLException {
        stream.writeInt(val1);
        // ...
    }
}
```

Now, assuming a package like the following:

```java
CREATE OR REPLACE PACKAGE p AS
  TYPE my_type IS RECORD (i NUMBER);
  TYPE my_type_table IS TABLE OF my_type;
  FUNCTION f (i my_type_table) RETURN my_type_table;
END p;
```

you can bind this type to the JDBC API like this:

```java
try (CallableStatement s = c.prepareCall(&quot;{ ? = call p.f (?) }&quot;)) {
    Array a = c.unwrap(OracleConnection.class)
               .createARRAY(&quot;P.MY_TYPE_TABLE&quot;, new MyType[] { new MyType(1) });

    try {
        s.registerOutParameter(1, Types.ARRAY, &quot;P.MY_TYPE_TABLE&quot;);
        s.setObject(2, a);
        s.execute();
        System.out.println(Arrays.asList((Object[])
            s.getArray(1).getArray(Map.of(&quot;P.MY_TYPE_TABLE&quot;, MyType.class))
        ));
    }
    finally {
        a.free();
    }
}
```

It&#39;s quite laborious, but you can do it. If using a third party library is an option, [jOOQ supports a code generator that can generate all of the above metadata for you][2], so your call will just be:

```java
MytypeTableRecord result = 
    P.f(configuration, new MyTypeTableRecord(new MyTypeRecord(1)));
```

Disclaimer: I work for the company behind jOOQ.


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.sql/java/sql/SQLData.html
  [2]: https://blog.jooq.org/painless-access-from-java-to-plsql-procedures-with-jooq/

You can do it with streams but there would probably be some internal iterations or other streams required or perhaps having to write a custom collector. And I assure you it is not as easy as the following:

Here I am using records to facilitate the demo.  They behave like immutable classes with getters auto-generated.  I modified the `toString()` of `NewView` for display.
```
record View(String getId, String getDocId, String getName) {
}

record NewView(String getId, String getName, List&lt;String&gt; getDocIds) {
	@Override
	public String toString() {
	    return getName + &quot;, &quot; + getId + &quot;, &quot; + getDocIds;
	}
}
```
The process creates a Map to hold the resulting NewView class with a common key.  I chose name, but `Id` would have also worked.  If the existing `key` is not present, a new NewValue instance is created.  That is then returned and the list is retrieved and the associated `docId` is added to the list.
```
List&lt;View&gt; viewList = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
viewList.add(new View(&quot;1234&quot;, &quot;ab123&quot;, &quot;john&quot;));
viewList.add(new View(&quot;1234&quot;, &quot;cd456&quot;, &quot;john&quot;));
viewList.add(new View(&quot;1234&quot;, &quot;ef789&quot;, &quot;john&quot;));
viewList.add(new View(&quot;5678&quot;, &quot;jh987&quot;, &quot;jack&quot;));
viewList.add(new View(&quot;5678&quot;, &quot;ij654&quot;, &quot;jack&quot;));
viewList.add(new View(&quot;5678&quot;, &quot;kl321&quot;, &quot;jack&quot;));
viewList.add(new View(&quot;9876&quot;, &quot;mn123&quot;, &quot;ben&quot;));
viewList.add(new View(&quot;9876&quot;, &quot;op456&quot;, &quot;ben&quot;));

Map&lt;String, NewView&gt; results = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();

for (View view : viewList) {
    results.computeIfAbsent(view.getName(),
	    v -&gt; new NewView(view.getId(), view.getName(),
		    new ArrayList&lt;&gt;()))
	    .getDocIds().add(view.getDocId());
}
```
The values are stored in a `Collection` and can be iterated as such to print.
```
for (NewView v : results.values()) {
    System.out.println(v);
}
```
prints
```
ben, 9876, [mn123, op456]
john, 1234, [ab123, cd456, ef789]
jack, 5678, [jh987, ij654, kl321]
```
For index retrieval you would need to add them to `List&lt;NewView&gt;`
```
List&lt;NewView&gt; newViewList = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(results.values());
System.out.println(newViewList.get(1));
```
prints
```
john, 1234, [ab123, cd456, ef789]

It can be done by in a single stream statement.

For that we can define a custom Collector via static method [`Collector.of()`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/stream/Collector.html#of(java.util.function.Supplier,java.util.function.BiConsumer,java.util.function.BinaryOperator,java.util.function.Function,java.util.stream.Collector.Characteristics...)) which would be used as a downstream of `groupingBy()` to perform mutable reduction of the `View` instances having the same `id` (*and consequently mapped to the same key*).

It would also require creating a custom accumulation type that would serve a mean of mutable reduction and eventually would be transformed into a `NewView`.

***Note** that* `NewView` *can also serve as the accumulation type, in case if it&#39;s mutable (I would make a safe assumption, that it&#39;s not and create a separate class for that purpose).*

That&#39;s how the stream producing the resulting list might look like:

```
List&lt;View&gt; viewList = // initialing the list
    
List&lt;NewView&gt; newViewList = viewList.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
        View::getId,
        Collector.of(
            ViewMerger::new,
            ViewMerger::accept,
            ViewMerger::merge,
            ViewMerger::toNewView
        )
    ))
    .values().stream().toList();
```

That&#39;s how such accumulation type might look like. For convenience, I&#39;ve implemented the contract of [`Consumer`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/function/Consumer.html) interface:

    public static class ViewMerger implements Consumer&lt;View&gt; {
        private String id;
        private String name;
        private List&lt;String&gt; docIds = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
        
        // no args-constructor
    
        @Override
        public void accept(View view) {
            if (id == null) id = view.getId();
            if (name == null) name = view.getName();
            
            docIds.add(view.getDocId());
        }
        
        public ViewMerger merge(ViewMerger other) {
            this.docIds.addAll(other.docIds);
            return this;
        }
        
        public NewView toNewView() {
            return new NewView(id, name, docIds);
        }
    }

