answers.body_markdown:
[`Map.of`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Map.html#of(K,V)) doesn&#39;t return a `HashMap`, it returns an [unmodifiable map](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Map.html#unmodifiable) (what type that is exactly is implementation-dependent and not important), so you can&#39;t assign it to a `HashMap`.

You can work around that by using the [`HashMap`&#39;s constructor](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/HashMap.html#%3Cinit%3E(java.util.Map)) that accepts (and makes a copy of) another map as an argument.

    HashMap&lt;String, String&gt; hashMap = new HashMap&lt;&gt;(Map.of(&quot;name&quot;, &quot;Murife&quot;));
